[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

You can't support partner's \Hs with only 2 of them so you bid your nice \S suit. Partner then jumps to 3\H. Now  

Here's where a lot of players go wrong. Since they only promised 4 \Ss with their first response they think they should now rebid them to show partner they had 5. And this <b>MIGHT</b> work if it turns out partner has 3 \Ss. Not only is this a risky bid, it is unnecessary. When partner jump rebid \Hs he showed 16-18 points and 6 \Hs. So you know of an 8-card fit and you know you should be in game. Bid 4\H.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "E:AQT93.A92.KQJ3.4 65.QJT6.96.J9863 KJ72.85.742.AKQ5 84.K743.AT85.T72"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1S pass 2C pass 2D pass 4S pass 4NT pass 5D pass 6S all pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "a0435a9b730d4ea1ba41de1d5f0c046afc610aaa25c380111ccc447689267d3f"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/major_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.  

As soon as partner opens 1\S you know you will settle for nothing less than the \S game. The problem with bidding 4\S right now is that partner will take you for the "weak-distributional-with-five-trumps" hand. So you temporize by first bidding 2\C. Partner rebids 2\D.  

You now jump to 4\S, completing the picture of an opening hand with good \S support. Partner bids 4NT. What say you? 

This is Blackwood so you answer 5\D for one Ace. Partner says 6\S.}

